:::summary
Gothic architecture is the medieval building style that produced the great cathedrals of Europe — Chartres, Notre-Dame de Paris, Canterbury, Cologne, Salisbury, and hundreds more — between approximately 1140 and 1500 AD. Characterized by pointed arches, ribbed vaulting, flying buttresses, and enormous stained-glass windows, the Gothic cathedral was not merely a building but a theological statement: a stone sermon proclaiming the glory of God, the beauty of the heavenly Jerusalem, and the aspirations of a civilization that understood itself as *Christendom*.
:::

